sentence = "the cat sat on the mat"

words = sentence.split()

counts = {}

for x in words:
    counts[x] = counts.get(x, 0) + 1
print(counts)


# Ok just for some notes, in a loop any VARIABLE[LOOP VAR like x] means look up the value stored under this key. Left of the equal size is always write, and right is read
# for dictionary values. a VARIABLE[LOOP VAR like x] + 1 on the right side finds whatever is stored under the word and just adds 1, 
# so if nothing is stored it gives a keyerror
# Square brackets as a whole is a lookup syntax that says grab this thing at this address, with dictionaries directly its "go grab this key". Parentheses are calling a 
# function or method so you always call something like .get with paraen
# .get is formated like .get(key, fallback) and its a safe way to dict lookup by fetching the value for a key, but returns the fallback instead of crashing if that key
# doesn't exist. if you do counts["cat"] and its not there it will blow up, counts.get("cat", 0) gives an out, returns 0, if cat isn't there
